1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,000
 Kako možete vidjeti od predstavljenja,Sem ću provoštiti jedan koncept od amerikanskog autora,John_Louis_Geddis,Predstrategy,Zagreb,Konstantin i svojom strategijskog zvrlj.

2
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:38,000
 A simple definition of grand strategy given by Geddes is a plan of action to achieve a long term objective.

3
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:51,000
 More precisely, it entails balancing limitless ambitions with inherently limited capabilities,linking current position to desired ends.

4
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 What makes a grand strategy grand is the significance of its goal.

5
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:07,000
 Is the founding of the Roman Empire or Lincoln's abolition of slavery rather than everyday choices like what I will wear today.

6
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:10,000
 Practicality is essential.

7
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:27,000
 As Geddes' account of Pericles suggests one must set a destination,prepare resources,motivate actors and adapt to shifting conditions,controlling some variables while engaging with others.

8
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:39,000
 The central challenge of every grand strategist is sustaining balance without losing sight of the ultimate destination which requires managing enduring polarities.

9
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:48,000
 What then are the central elements of,in my opinion,Constantin's strategy?

10
00:01:48,000 --> 00:02:03,000
 the unification or more precisely recentralization of the empire,namely the abolition of Diocletian's tetrarchy and no less importantly the christianization of the empire.

11
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:18,000
 The latter can most reliably be dated to October 312,marking at least the first step toward transforming the empire into a christian one.

12
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,000
 For example,Constantin decides to become the sole ruler of the empire.

13
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:27,000
 And after battle at the Milvian bridge,he certainly also aim to be a christian empire.

14
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:33,000
 Desiring from that point onwards that christianity became the empire's primary religion.

15
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:48,000
 Of course,Constantin's relationship with christianity is a complex subject and unlikely ever to be fully clarified.

16
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:54,000
 What appears probable up to the battle of the Milvian bridge is the following:

17
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:07,000
 He first encountered the christian god christianity and christians in his youth,likely under the strong influence of his deeply devout mother Helena.

18
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:18,000
 From his father,he probably received information about the policy of relative tolerance towards christians that they later pursued.

19
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:28,000
 After proclaimed Augustus in 306,Constantin himself adapted a similar policy of tolerance.

20
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:36,000
 By 314th,at the council of Arles,he acted in a manner akin to a bishop.

21
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:42,000
 And by that point may even have begun privately to believe in the christian god.

22
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 Or at least to recognize him as equal to the other gods and deities he had encountered in the Balkans,in the army,in the Rome,and elsewhere.

23
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:07,000
 At this stage,Constantin wished to be the sole ruler while maintaining a special though not yet fully defined relationship with christians whom he certainly did not persecute.

24
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:19,000
 What follows is an exceptionally important moment.

25
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:32,000
 The vision Constantine experienced on October 28th when near Rome,he saw a sign above the sun that would glide him to victory over his rival.

26
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:42,000
 This sign is perhaps best described by the English term christogram and combination of letters forming an abbreviation of Christ's name.

27
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 There is no doubt however that the victory over Maxentius should be regarded as the moment when Constantine concluded that the time had come for an open public identification with christianity.

28
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:02,000
 Or more precisely with christianity.

29
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:07,000
 He had just won a major battle and entered Rome.

30
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:14,000
 And all could see that this victory had been achieved with the aid of Christ and his divine father.

31
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:32,000
 The christian god had now turned his face towards Constantine and the sign of his son the Christ appeared on the shield of every soldier who secured for him rule over the western half of the empire.

32
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:58,000
 Can we therefore already conclude that Constantine became dependent on the christian god since should he lose that crucial support his earthly successes in this moment the rule over the western half of the empire and with them the vision of a unified christian empire would collapse.

33
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:07,000
 In all probability and as I could see from the sources yes.

34
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:13,000
 The new ruler of the western part of the empire was in contemporary terms a politician on a clear rise.

35
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 Yet he ruled territories where christians were a minority despite having just won with the aid of the christian god.

36
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:28,000
 It was therefore the moment for a first major step.

37
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:43,000
 The new ruler of the west presented himself as a man who worshipped only one christian god whose support he enjoyed and to whom he thus owed gratitude.

38
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:50,000
 was not Galerius' edict of toleration confirmed at the milvian bridge.

39
00:06:50,000 --> 00:07:01,000
 And more importantly did not the victor under the sign of the cross need to affirm at least the equality of christians and their god with others in the empire.

40
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 Hence with the eastern empire weakened Constantine issued a document known as the edict of milan which corresponded almost perfectly to the second goal of his strategy.

41
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:18,000
 Christianity became equal to other religions throughout the empire.

42
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:24,000
 And he publicly thanked Christ for his victory.

43
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:26,000
 Christianity now prospered.

44
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:34,000
 It was legalized and the most powerful man in the empire was its undisputed supporter, protector and promoter.

45
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 At this point the sincerity of Constantine's conversion mattered less.

46
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:45,000
 Although in my opinion there is little reason to doubt it.

47
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:54,000
 What kind of christian you may ask issues coinage celebrating the pagan son god or the soul invictus.

48
00:07:54,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 And in 321 even establishes a special day in his honor.

49
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:05,000
 At first glance a poor one but it seems only at first glance.

50
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:10,000
 Constantine wished to retain the favor of the pagan majority.

51
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:15,000
 And thus maintain for a time the empire foremost deity.

52
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:17,000
 The sun god.

53
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 Yet is it not Christ also the light of the world.

54
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:26,000
 And therefore capable of being identified with the sun.

55
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 Here as with the christogram we encounter another in my opinion master stroke of propaganda.

56
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:43,000
 Likewise if speculation is correct that Lysinius has accepted the edict of Milan merely for tactical reason.

57
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 And subsequently reverted to milder forms of persecution.

58
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 What kind of christian emperor or christ representative on earth would fail to protect christians.

59
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:02,000
 Once again the two central motives in my opinion of Constantine's strategy converged.

60
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:06,000
 Without the east he could not be the sole emperor.

61
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:15,000
 And without safeguarding christians in the east he could not satisfy the god who wanted the security of christians and their church.

62
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:20,000
 By September 324 he had achieved both aims.

63
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 He became sole emperor and the first christian emperor.

64
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:34,000
 A shrewd politician like Constantine must have known that state intervention in church affairs carried a less favorable side.

65
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,000
 And thus his numerous interventions are well documented.

66
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 Beginning with the synod of Ireland in 314 and the Donatist controversy.

67
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:53,000
 The most significant of course occurred in Nicaea in 325.

68
00:09:54,000 --> 00:10:01,000
 The precise nature of the creed imposed or agreed upon there can be debated at length.

69
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:06,000
 But there is no doubt that the council confirmed Constantine's new role.

70
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:24,000
 was defined as that of christian knighted apostle or first bishop compelled to resolve a theological dispute that threatened the stability of a newly unified empire.

71
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 Constantine appeared conciliatory at Nicaea yet also resolute and clear in his aims.

72
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 The council convened in the imperial residence, the emperor was present throughout, and his western bishop played a leading part in drafting the document.

73
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:55,000
 At Nicaea, so we may conclude, religion was politics and both converged in the persons of Constantine.

74
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:14,000
 From the vast body of literature on this subject, Constantine seems best defined by four terms.

75
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:20,000
 Centralization, christianity, syncretism, and propaganda.

76
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:32,000
 In other words, one emperor at the head of one empire from 312 onward after the Milvian bridge,

77
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:39,000
 certainly a christian emperor ruling an empire that was itself becoming christian,

78
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:47,000
 a flexible or pragmatic approach to elevating christianity to the status of the empire foremost religion,

79
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:56,000
 or at least that of the imperial household that can mean the same and masterful use of symbols.

80
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 Constantine died in 337.

81
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:10,000
 And if my interpretation of his grand strategy is broadly correct, it can be concluded that he succeeded.

82
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:22,000
 He died near the first christian city of a unified empire, in which christianity has become the primary and the most important religion,

83
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:25,000
 and the most important religion.

84
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:29,000
 Of course, no strategy is flawless.

85
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:34,000
 So, nor was Constantine's.

86
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:43,000
 For example, the biggest strategist in the modern history, let's say, Abraham Lincoln,

87
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:58,000
 who abolished slavery by balancing act or he presented the abolition of slavery as a military necessity during the American Civil War.

88
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:08,000
 And that kind of approach left some consequences that are still felt in American society.

89
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:14,000
 For example, another great strategist of the 20th century, American President Roosevelt,

90
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:19,000
 was undisputably first winner of the Second World War.

91
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:23,000
 American power was spread all over the world.

92
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:33,000
 And the main continental adversaries of the United States of America were, like Germany, like Soviet Union,

93
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:37,000
 on the winning side were, in material ways, ruined.

94
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:46,000
 They were not the real competence for the American power.

95
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:50,000
 So, nor was Constantine's flawless.

96
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:55,000
 He left behind the challenge of Christians outside the empire.

97
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:08,000
 And it can be stated, maybe, that they became the fifth column when the Christianity became, especially when it later became the state religion.

98
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:12,000
 In other states like Persia or some others.

99
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:19,000
 There are, then, the latent adorns of fusing church and state.

100
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:27,000
 And the temptation of defining orthodoxy through political means.

101
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:40,000
 We should never forget that, in my opinion, what was agreed at Nicaea was, first and foremost, a political act.

102
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:48,000
 According to the sources, however, he died as the thirteenth apostle.

103
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:52,000
 Not Christ himself, but the one closest to him.

104
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:56,000
 Standing far above the remaining twelve.

105
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:06,000
 So, you will probably agree with me that all of this is rather successful grand strategy.

106
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:07,000
 Thank you very much.

